\[ \qquad x + 2 \geq 0 \implies x \geq -2 \] That was easy. But what if $f(x)$ is a little more complicated, say a rational function, like \[ \quad f(x) = \frac{(x-1)\cdot (x+3)}{x-2}, x\neq 2 \] When is $f(x) \geq 0$ and when is it $\leq 0$? One only needs to be methodical to solve such inequalities. First, determine the "roots" of $f(x)$ as shown below % \begin{align} \begin{tabular}{lN}
\hline & \text{Roots} \\ \hline Numerator & x = 1, -3 \\ \hline Denominator & x = 2 \\ \hline \end{tabular} \end{align} %text Then \underline\text{split the number line at the roots} and determine the sign of each individual term in $f(x)$ -- and therefore of $f(x)$ % \begin{align} \begin{tabular}{NNNNN}
\hline & x < -3 & (-3,1) & (1,2) & > 2 \\ \hline x-1 & - & - & + & + \\ \hline x + 3 & - & + & + & + \\ \hline x - 2 & - & - & - & + \\ \hline \frac{(x-1)\cdot (x+3)}{x-2} & - & + & - & + \\ \hline \end{tabular} \end{align} %text %
